data.content:
This is a **timeout enforcement** pattern — `Thread.Abort` is used to kill work that exceeds a deadline. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is removed (`SYSLIB0006`).

## What breaks and why

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 behavior |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

The fundamental shift: **preemptive** cancellation (runtime injects an exception) → **cooperative** cancellation (code voluntarily checks a `CancellationToken`).

## Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var task = Task.Run(work, cts.Token);

        try
        {
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    // Preferred: overload that passes the token to cooperative work
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
        var token = cts.Token;

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(token), token);
            return task.WaitAsync(token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Usage

```csharp
var executor = new TimedExecutor();

// Simple (fire-and-forget token — work won't be interrupted mid-CPU-burst)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeAnswer(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// Cooperative (work checks the token — stops promptly)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(ct =>
{
    foreach (var item in largeDataSet)
    {
        ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return BuildResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

## Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Solution |
|---|---|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** — the simple overload (`Func<T>`) can't interrupt CPU-bound work mid-execution | Use the `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload and call `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** — leaks internal timers | Always wrap in `using` |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish timeout from external cancellation |
| **Blocking I/O won't respond to cancellation** | Replace synchronous I/O (`socket.Receive`, `Thread.Sleep`) with async overloads that accept `CancellationToken` |
| **Truly uncooperative code** (can't modify it to check token) | Move it to a child **process** and use `Process.Kill()` — this is the only safe equivalent of the old `Thread.Abort` |
| **`Task.Run` abandonment** — when the timeout fires, the `Task.Run` delegate may keep running in the background | This is by design. Cooperative code will exit at the next checkpoint; uncooperative code will finish eventually. Monitor with logging if needed |

The migrated code is fully `.NET 8`-compatible with zero `SYSLIB0006` warnings and no `Thread.Abort`-related APIs.
